egypt and the middle east nonviral gene medicine for hemophilia a core  biolaboratory mutagenesis carcinogenesis and tetratogenesis  recently added grants stellenbosch university clinical trials unit sunctu t cell response to listeria monocytogenes infection hiv vpu and bstcd mucosal live vector vaccine against recurrent clostridium difficile infections role of subactivationthreshold tcr interactions in maintaining t cell memory   abstract goals the repair of doublestranded dna breaks in drosophila mitotic cells will be analyzed genetically such breaks can be repaired by two main classes of mechanisms recombinational and endjoining these classes differ significantly in the kinds of repair products that are produced within each class multiple individual pathways are thought to exist the goal is to perform a genetic dissection of these mechanisms for each major pathway the genetic consequences and the structure of the repair products will be determined examination of these parameters in a series of mutations at loci involved in the repair processes will reveal how the pathways differ and the type of repair that is affected approach excision of p transposable elements provides a useful way to produce doublestrand breaks at specific known locations in the genome these excisions can be regulated by p transposase in addition two sitespecific endonucleases ho and iscei have been shown to function in drosophila these three methods will be used to generate specific doublestrand breaks in vivo under welldefined genetic conditions a series of tests using these sitespecific breaks will be applied in different genetic backgrounds to provide a detailed description of the consequences of doublestrand break repair different pathways for repair will be distinguished by mutating genes thought to be involved with one or more mechanism seven genetic loci involved with repair were selected to include a variety of such functions two recentlydeveloped methods will be used to obtain mutations the first generates p insertions in or near the targeted genes and the second uses these insertions to obtain flanking deletions which knock out the genes medical significance dna repair is recognized as crucial to maintaining the stability of the genome especially in species with complex genomes human mutations in many dna repair genes including the human homologs of several of the loci in the present study cause predisposition to cancer a better understanding of these repair processes can come from studies using drosophila which like humans has a relatively complex genome and multicellular organization thus requiring a high level of genomic stability at the same time drosophila gives researchers the genetic tools needed to analyze the multipathway repair system   funding agency agencynational institute of health nih institutenational institute of general medical sciences nigms typeresearch project r project rgm application  study sectiongenetics study section gen program officerrhoades marcus m project start project end budget start budget end support year fiscal year total cost indirect cost   institution nameuniversity of wisconsin madison departmentgenetics typeschools of medicine duns  citymadison statewi countryunited states zip code   related projects   publications johnsonschlitz dena m flores carlos engels william r  multiplepathway analysis of doublestrand break repair mutations in drosophila plos genet e preston christine r flores carlos c engels william r  differential usage of alternative pathways of doublestrand break repair in drosophila genetics  preston christine r flores carlos engels william r  agedependent usage of doublestrandbreak repair pathways curr biol  johnsonschlitz dena m engels william r  the effect of gap length on doublestrand break repair in drosophila genetics  johnsonschlitz dena engels william r  template disruptions and failure of double holliday junction dissolution during doublestrand break repair in drosophila blm mutants